issue.title: Fix issues with ArmNN build setup

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: 
Fix some issues with the build setup for the ArmNN EP.
 - Document that the ACL paths are required
 - Fix the include paths for building the ArmNN provider library
 - Fix the way the ArmNN libraries are included 
   - make inclusion mechanism and library order consistent 
   - don't use link_libraries as that results in adding them to the link list of everything, including binaries like the MLAS unit test program which has no dependency on the ArmNN libraries
 - Fix the onnxruntime_perf_test link list to used the external libraries list for consistency, and remove some redundant entries due to that change
 - Fix the ArmNN gemm.h file to include the ORT GemmHelper correctly

**Motivation and Context**
#6486
#6421

body:
Hi @skottmckay, thank you for the fix.
Regarding the issues:
- You can build ArmNN separately following https://github.com/ARM-software/armnn/blob/branches/armnn_20_11/BuildGuideCrossCompilation.md. Here should be a more updated version of the documentation.
- Most of our tests used a cross-toolchain for the cross-compilation step. ACL and ArmNN libraries are present in the toolchain and the custom paths are not needed. The option was added for the cases when the libraries are from a different version. It could be that we did not see that. Other thing would be that ArmNN EP does not necessary need ACL if the library is not linked dynamic, which was the case some time ago. That means that the ACL library was integrated inside ArmNN and we did not need the extra step. This did not affect the build in any sense, but it was to specify if you use an external library or not.
- We used link_library because in some instances, the cross-toolchain would not see them if not stated otherwise.
- Regarding the gemm function, like other instances, there are some files in the ACL and ArmNN EP that use CPU EP files for fallback operations in case the ONNX Runtime execute functions more generic than ACL and ArmNN could provide. This means that some changes in the CPU files path will affect the paths in those.

Hi @Andrews548. Thanks for the info. Much appreciated. 

Whilst ArmNN may not need the ACL libraries, it includes headers from ACL and at least needs the ACL include paths. Is that not intentional? 

Any feedback on how the ONNX proto file should be processed? If you're building with ORT I would expect you'd want to use the version of ONNX that ORT is using instead of an arbitrary commit id from your build instructions. Is that correct? And if so, how should one resolve the discrepancy that ArmNN is using full protobuf and ORT is using protobuf-lite by default?

Hi @skottmckay, sorry for the delay.

ArmNN Execution Provider uses the NEON backend from ACL. Regarding include paths, i do not know, inside of ONNX Runtime, to be files in ArmNN EP that needs ACL headers. If you found any such problems, it could be from the ACL library linkage. Then again, we used the environment that already links both set of headers by default so it could be a corner-case here.

As for protobuf, the recommendations were to build the ArmNN library without the parsers and protobuf supports. This means that that library would not be used on its own outside ONNX Runtime, but the discrepancy would disappear.

This issue has been automatically marked as stale due to inactivity and will be closed in 7 days if no further activity occurs. If further support is needed, please provide an update and/or more details.
